WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.996 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.996 --> 00:00:04.491 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.491 --> 00:00:07.984 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.984 --> 00:00:11.780 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.780 --> 00:00:16.640 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: OK, so remember
that projection theory

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:18.717 align:middle line:90%
works differently over--

00:00:18.717 --> 00:00:20.800 align:middle line:84%
if you look in finite
fields, it works differently

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:23.880 align:middle line:84%
over a prime field
or a not prime field.

00:00:23.880 --> 00:00:25.370 align:middle line:90%
And here was the key example.

00:00:25.370 --> 00:00:32.439 align:middle line:90%


00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:34.320 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
do projection theory

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:37.960 align:middle line:90%
and Fq and q is p squared.

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:42.040 align:middle line:84%
And our set of points is
going to be Fp squared, which

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:45.200 align:middle line:90%
is a subset of Fq squared.

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:47.160 align:middle line:84%
And our set of
directions is going

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:51.440 align:middle line:84%
to be Fp, which
is a subset of Fq.

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:55.560 align:middle line:84%
So remember that
if theta is in Fq,

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:59.730 align:middle line:84%
then pi theta is going to be
a projection, a linear map,

00:00:59.730 --> 00:01:06.310 align:middle line:84%
from Fq squared to Fq, which
is given by pi theta of x1,

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:10.890 align:middle line:90%
x2 is x1 plus theta x2.

00:01:10.890 --> 00:01:13.690 align:middle line:84%
So this is our
set of directions.

00:01:13.690 --> 00:01:17.210 align:middle line:84%
And then S, which
is the maximum size

00:01:17.210 --> 00:01:22.530 align:middle line:84%
of the projection of x
over all these directions

00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:37.930 align:middle line:84%
is p because pi theta of x
is just Fp for theta and D.

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:41.810 align:middle line:84%
So if you just write down the
sizes of all the things in this

00:01:41.810 --> 00:01:44.990 align:middle line:84%
important example,
x is p squared,

00:01:44.990 --> 00:01:51.810 align:middle line:84%
which is q and S and D are
p which is q to the 1/2.

00:01:51.810 --> 00:01:55.130 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, notice that
the size of each projection

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:57.470 align:middle line:84%
is the square root of
the size of the set.

00:01:57.470 --> 00:02:04.990 align:middle line:90%


00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:09.389 align:middle line:84%
So nothing like this is
supposed to happen over Fp.

00:02:09.389 --> 00:02:12.750 align:middle line:84%
There's a hard open
conjecture that

00:02:12.750 --> 00:02:16.290 align:middle line:84%
gives bounds that are much
stronger than this example.

00:02:16.290 --> 00:02:17.790 align:middle line:84%
But the techniques
that we've talked

00:02:17.790 --> 00:02:21.810 align:middle line:84%
about for most of the class
do not depend on the field.

00:02:21.810 --> 00:02:24.310 align:middle line:84%
So the double counting does
not distinguish prime fields

00:02:24.310 --> 00:02:25.577 align:middle line:90%
from nonprime fields.

00:02:25.577 --> 00:02:27.910 align:middle line:84%
And the Fourier method does
not distinguish prime fields

00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:28.920 align:middle line:90%
from nonprime fields.

00:02:28.920 --> 00:02:31.990 align:middle line:90%


00:02:31.990 --> 00:02:36.550 align:middle line:84%
The Szemerédi-Trotter theorem
proves that this numerology

00:02:36.550 --> 00:02:40.870 align:middle line:84%
cannot happen for a
set of points in R2,

00:02:40.870 --> 00:02:44.790 align:middle line:84%
but the proof is very important,
but it has some limitations

00:02:44.790 --> 00:02:45.810 align:middle line:90%
in how it could apply.

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:48.710 align:middle line:84%
It certainly won't
apply over Fp.

00:02:48.710 --> 00:02:52.030 align:middle line:84%
And it also doesn't seem to help
very much from the point of view

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:56.358 align:middle line:84%
of sets of balls in R2 with
some kind of spacing condition.

00:02:56.358 --> 00:02:57.900 align:middle line:84%
So it depends what
spacing condition,

00:02:57.900 --> 00:02:59.858 align:middle line:84%
but for the most interesting
spacing condition,

00:02:59.858 --> 00:03:03.000 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't help very much.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.690 align:middle line:84%
Nevertheless, we know that
this cannot happen over finite

00:03:06.690 --> 00:03:07.190 align:middle line:90%
fields.

00:03:07.190 --> 00:03:10.120 align:middle line:90%


00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:13.000 align:middle line:84%
And the main theorem that
we'll-- so this week,

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.200 align:middle line:84%
we'll prove a theorem that
says that this cannot happen.

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:19.020 align:middle line:84%
So this is the theorem of
Bourgain, Katz, and Tau.

00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:24.240 align:middle line:90%


00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:28.640 align:middle line:84%
So again, Katz-Tau
projection theorem--

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:30.380 align:middle line:90%
it says the following.

00:03:30.380 --> 00:03:38.440 align:middle line:84%
So if we have x in Fp squared,
and let's say that the size of x

00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:46.520 align:middle line:84%
is p to the S, where S is
somewhere between 0 and 2.

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:52.160 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a set
of directions in Fp,

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:56.570 align:middle line:84%
and set of directions
will be p to the t.

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:59.100 align:middle line:90%
And t is bigger than 0.

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:03.730 align:middle line:90%


00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:11.810 align:middle line:84%
So then, if you look at the
maximum size of a projection,

00:04:11.810 --> 00:04:16.089 align:middle line:84%
it's significantly bigger
than half over the square root

00:04:16.089 --> 00:04:18.850 align:middle line:90%
of the size of x.

00:04:18.850 --> 00:04:26.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is bigger than p to
the S over 22 plus epsilon

00:04:26.530 --> 00:04:30.570 align:middle line:84%
where this epsilon only
depends on S and t.

00:04:30.570 --> 00:04:31.600 align:middle line:90%
It's bigger than 0.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:43.890 align:middle line:90%


00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:46.710 align:middle line:84%
So some remarks
about the epsilon--

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:47.990 align:middle line:90%
it's an explicit function.

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:50.448 align:middle line:84%
I just don't write it down
because it's a little bit messy.

00:04:50.448 --> 00:04:52.250 align:middle line:90%
For example, it's continuous.

00:04:52.250 --> 00:04:53.870 align:middle line:84%
It's not that hard
to write it down,

00:04:53.870 --> 00:04:57.170 align:middle line:84%
but it is also pretty small,
pretty disappointingly small.

00:04:57.170 --> 00:05:01.732 align:middle line:90%


00:05:01.732 --> 00:05:04.570 align:middle line:84%
There's also something called
Bourgain's projection theorem,

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:07.270 align:middle line:84%
which is what Pablo Shmerkin is
going to talk about today, which

00:05:07.270 --> 00:05:11.430 align:middle line:84%
is the analog of this over in
the setting of the reel of balls

00:05:11.430 --> 00:05:13.790 align:middle line:90%
in R2.

00:05:13.790 --> 00:05:18.950 align:middle line:84%
So there's an analog of this
example using C2 instead of R2.

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:21.030 align:middle line:84%
And then Bourgain's
projection theorem

00:05:21.030 --> 00:05:24.020 align:middle line:84%
is the analog of this theorem
that rules out that example.

00:05:24.020 --> 00:05:33.350 align:middle line:90%


00:05:33.350 --> 00:05:42.990 align:middle line:84%
This is an analogous
theorem for balls in R2.

00:05:42.990 --> 00:05:48.270 align:middle line:84%
And these two theorems, in spite
of the fact that this epsilon is

00:05:48.270 --> 00:05:53.320 align:middle line:84%
very small, are very
important landmark results

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:55.360 align:middle line:84%
in the field of
projection theory,

00:05:55.360 --> 00:06:00.360 align:middle line:84%
and they play a key role
in many applications.

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:02.880 align:middle line:84%
This Bourgain projection
theorem, it plays a key role

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:08.000 align:middle line:84%
in getting the sharp projection
estimates in R2, the recent work

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.720 align:middle line:84%
that Pablo Shmerkin and
others were involved in.

00:06:11.720 --> 00:06:13.400 align:middle line:84%
This Bourgain
projection theorem also

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:18.320 align:middle line:84%
plays an important role in
the solution of the k problem.

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:21.460 align:middle line:84%
And this finite field projection
theorem, as well as this one,

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:24.800 align:middle line:84%
have an important role in
some interesting applications

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:28.880 align:middle line:84%
about how fast
different processes mix.

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:34.760 align:middle line:84%
If you take some generators of
a finite group like SL2 or Fp

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:37.160 align:middle line:84%
and then they make
a random walk,

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:40.080 align:middle line:84%
how fast does this random
walk become evenly distributed

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:41.840 align:middle line:90%
in SL2 Fp?

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:44.310 align:middle line:84%
This is an important
ingredient in studying that.

00:06:44.310 --> 00:06:49.597 align:middle line:90%


00:06:49.597 --> 00:06:51.680 align:middle line:84%
So in spite of the fact
that the epsilon is small,

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:53.193 align:middle line:84%
these theorems are
very important,

00:06:53.193 --> 00:06:54.860 align:middle line:84%
and they're also
qualitatively different

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:57.580 align:middle line:84%
from the other theorems because
they're sensitive to what kind

00:06:57.580 --> 00:06:59.260 align:middle line:90%
of field we're working in.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:06:59.820 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:04.980 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What is the
analog of p for balls in R2?

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:06.460 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: The
analog of p-- so we

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:08.220 align:middle line:84%
would have the
setting would be you'd

00:07:08.220 --> 00:07:10.860 align:middle line:84%
have unit balls and
a ball of radius R.

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:12.960 align:middle line:90%
And R is the analog of p.

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:16.460 align:middle line:90%


00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:19.340 align:middle line:84%
So all the sizes of things,
we could think of them

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:21.980 align:middle line:90%
as powers of R. Yeah?

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:23.980 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do the proofs
use similar arguments

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:25.462 align:middle line:84%
or are they
completely different?

00:07:25.462 --> 00:07:27.420 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: The question
is, do these two proofs

00:07:27.420 --> 00:07:30.620 align:middle line:84%
use similar arguments or are
they completely different?

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:33.780 align:middle line:84%
There are multiple proofs of
this, but at least one of them

00:07:33.780 --> 00:07:38.070 align:middle line:84%
is very similar to this with
one layer of additional ideas.

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:41.080 align:middle line:90%


00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.380 align:middle line:84%
So my plan is that
we'll do this,

00:07:43.380 --> 00:07:45.920 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll talk about the
additional ideas to do this.

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:49.430 align:middle line:90%


00:07:49.430 --> 00:07:50.790 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:54.390 align:middle line:84%
Well, so the key difference
between Fq and Fp

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:59.630 align:middle line:84%
is that Fq has a subfield
and Fp has no subfield.

00:07:59.630 --> 00:08:02.650 align:middle line:84%
Now it's elementary to check
that Fp has no subfield.

00:08:02.650 --> 00:08:05.610 align:middle line:84%
But because we're proving some
kind of quantitative estimates,

00:08:05.610 --> 00:08:09.230 align:middle line:84%
we need some
quantitative lemma that

00:08:09.230 --> 00:08:11.375 align:middle line:84%
says that Fp not
only has no subfield,

00:08:11.375 --> 00:08:13.750 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't have anything
that's kind of approximately

00:08:13.750 --> 00:08:15.750 align:middle line:90%
a subfield.

00:08:15.750 --> 00:08:24.470 align:middle line:84%
So the main goal for today will
be to develop lemmas like that.

00:08:24.470 --> 00:08:28.350 align:middle line:84%
And let me show you-- so here's
the first version of lemma

00:08:28.350 --> 00:08:32.875 align:middle line:90%
like that, lemma 1.

00:08:32.875 --> 00:08:33.750 align:middle line:90%
Actually, let me do--

00:08:33.750 --> 00:08:35.167 align:middle line:84%
I think we need a
little notation.

00:08:35.167 --> 00:08:41.870 align:middle line:90%


00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:46.390 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that A
is a subset of Fp.

00:08:46.390 --> 00:08:51.160 align:middle line:84%
If I write A plus A,
then that means the set

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:55.120 align:middle line:84%
of all the sums a1 plus
a2 where a1 and a2 are

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:59.120 align:middle line:90%
in A. We could write A times A.

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:03.640 align:middle line:84%
That's the set of all the
products a1 times a2, a1,

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:07.180 align:middle line:90%
and a2 in A, and so on.

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:09.720 align:middle line:84%
So you can write a lot of
similar things like this,

00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:12.840 align:middle line:84%
and I think it'll be
clear what they all mean.

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:15.600 align:middle line:84%
But if it's not, of course,
we'll talk about it.

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:17.140 align:middle line:90%
So here's the lemma.

00:09:17.140 --> 00:09:23.440 align:middle line:84%
It's a quantitative lemma that
says that no subset behaves

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:26.620 align:middle line:90%
too much like a subfield.

00:09:26.620 --> 00:09:31.160 align:middle line:84%
So it says if A
is a subset of Fp,

00:09:31.160 --> 00:09:40.080 align:middle line:84%
then either one option is
that A minus A over A minus A

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:41.350 align:middle line:90%
is all of Fp.

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:45.080 align:middle line:90%


00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:56.780 align:middle line:84%
And the second option is that
if you multiply and add stuff

00:09:56.780 --> 00:10:00.940 align:middle line:84%
in and subtract stuff, a lot
of times, it will get bigger.

00:10:00.940 --> 00:10:02.700 align:middle line:90%
2, 3, 4, 5, 6--

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:03.880 align:middle line:90%
6 might be enough.

00:10:03.880 --> 00:10:04.920 align:middle line:90%
I think it might be 8.

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:14.120 align:middle line:90%


00:10:14.120 --> 00:10:17.460 align:middle line:84%
So one possibility is if you
multiply, add, and subtract

00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:20.220 align:middle line:84%
elements of A a
lot of times, then

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:23.140 align:middle line:84%
you get a lot more
stuff than just A.

00:10:23.140 --> 00:10:26.180 align:middle line:84%
So this says A is not
too close to a subfield.

00:10:26.180 --> 00:10:30.540 align:middle line:84%
And the other options is if
you do this, you get all of Fp.

00:10:30.540 --> 00:10:33.480 align:middle line:84%
Now, of course, A could have
been almost all of Fp already.

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:35.860 align:middle line:84%
So then it is kind
of almost a field.

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:39.060 align:middle line:84%
But if A was originally
a lot smaller than Fp,

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:55.530 align:middle line:84%
then, in this case, this thing
is a lot bigger than A. Cool.

00:10:55.530 --> 00:11:06.550 align:middle line:90%


00:11:06.550 --> 00:11:08.360 align:middle line:90%
So here is the proof--

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:11.110 align:middle line:90%


00:11:11.110 --> 00:11:12.530 align:middle line:90%
observation one.

00:11:12.530 --> 00:11:16.870 align:middle line:90%


00:11:16.870 --> 00:11:25.230 align:middle line:84%
So if c is not in A
minus A over A minus A,

00:11:25.230 --> 00:11:32.380 align:middle line:84%
then A plus cA has
size a squared.

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:41.878 align:middle line:90%


00:11:41.878 --> 00:11:44.580 align:middle line:84%
Let me make sure it's clear
what all the notation means.

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:48.700 align:middle line:84%
So if I write this thing, I have
four copies of A. So take a1,

00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:52.980 align:middle line:84%
a2, a3, a4, any four guys in A,
and plug them in for the capital

00:11:52.980 --> 00:11:53.480 align:middle line:90%
A's.

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:57.360 align:middle line:84%
All the things you can get,
that's what this set is.

00:11:57.360 --> 00:11:59.440 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, over
here, the lowercase c

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:01.800 align:middle line:90%
is a particular element of Fp.

00:12:01.800 --> 00:12:07.320 align:middle line:84%
And this means take any
a1 and a2 and do this.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:13.800 align:middle line:84%
So the proof of observation
one is quite simple.

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:20.085 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that I have two
different elements in here

00:12:20.085 --> 00:12:21.460 align:middle line:84%
but that are equal
to each other.

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:29.800 align:middle line:84%
So suppose a1 plus a2 is the
same as a1 prime plus a2 prime.

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:33.600 align:middle line:84%
Well, if I do a little algebra,
I can solve this for c.

00:12:33.600 --> 00:12:41.880 align:middle line:84%
And I discovered that c is a1
prime minus a1 divided by a2

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:49.060 align:middle line:84%
minus a2 prime, which is an
A minus A. So if c is not

00:12:49.060 --> 00:12:54.860 align:middle line:84%
an A minus A-- sorry, which is
an A minus A over A minus A--

00:12:54.860 --> 00:12:58.140 align:middle line:84%
so if c is not in
here, then all of

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:00.920 align:middle line:84%
these different representations
are actually different numbers.

00:13:00.920 --> 00:13:02.530 align:middle line:84%
So the size of this
set is A squared.

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:10.020 align:middle line:90%


00:13:10.020 --> 00:13:11.740 align:middle line:84%
Now if you want to
be really careful,

00:13:11.740 --> 00:13:15.340 align:middle line:84%
maybe we should worry about
whether I have divided by 0.

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:20.682 align:middle line:84%
But if a2 is equal to a2
prime, then the only way

00:13:20.682 --> 00:13:22.140 align:middle line:84%
that the top equation
could be true

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:24.780 align:middle line:84%
is if also a1 is
equal to a1 prime.

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:28.740 align:middle line:84%
And then I just
have the same thing.

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:29.780 align:middle line:90%
All right, great.

00:13:29.780 --> 00:13:32.900 align:middle line:90%


00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:41.590 align:middle line:84%
So if I can locate some c that
is in the ring of stuff I can

00:13:41.590 --> 00:13:45.310 align:middle line:84%
make by adding and multiplying--
maybe if I can add and subtract

00:13:45.310 --> 00:13:48.590 align:middle line:84%
and multiply and divide a bunch
of elements of A and I can

00:13:48.590 --> 00:13:52.030 align:middle line:84%
locate some c which
is not in here,

00:13:52.030 --> 00:13:56.070 align:middle line:84%
then I can use this observation,
and I can get some--

00:13:56.070 --> 00:13:59.160 align:middle line:84%
I can show that I can build
out of A many different things.

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:01.750 align:middle line:90%


00:14:01.750 --> 00:14:03.370 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:07.695 align:middle line:90%


00:14:07.695 --> 00:14:09.590 align:middle line:84%
Now somewhere in
our proof, we have

00:14:09.590 --> 00:14:13.390 align:middle line:90%
to use that Fp is a prime field.

00:14:13.390 --> 00:14:16.310 align:middle line:84%
It wouldn't work in Fq and
we haven't used it yet.

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:17.910 align:middle line:84%
Well, how are we
going to use it.

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:19.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's just remember
how we would prove

00:14:19.790 --> 00:14:23.270 align:middle line:90%
that Fp is a prime field--

00:14:23.270 --> 00:14:26.518 align:middle line:84%
sorry, how would we prove
that Fp has no subfields?

00:14:26.518 --> 00:14:27.810 align:middle line:90%
How are we going to prove that?

00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:33.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, if it had a subfield
it would have to contain 1,

00:14:33.670 --> 00:14:35.170 align:middle line:84%
and then it would
have to contain--

00:14:35.170 --> 00:14:36.370 align:middle line:84%
then it would be
closed under addition,

00:14:36.370 --> 00:14:38.410 align:middle line:84%
so it would have to contain
2 and 3 and 4 and so on.

00:14:38.410 --> 00:14:40.243 align:middle line:84%
And then it would have
to contain all of Fp.

00:14:40.243 --> 00:14:44.930 align:middle line:90%


00:14:44.930 --> 00:14:48.530 align:middle line:84%
So we're basically going to use
that argument in observation

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:49.030 align:middle line:90%
two.

00:14:49.030 --> 00:15:17.090 align:middle line:90%


00:15:17.090 --> 00:15:26.810 align:middle line:84%
So observation two, if A minus
A over A minus A is not Fp,

00:15:26.810 --> 00:15:34.570 align:middle line:84%
then there exists some B
in A minus A over A minus A

00:15:34.570 --> 00:15:39.820 align:middle line:84%
so that B plus 1 is
not in A minus A over A

00:15:39.820 --> 00:16:04.340 align:middle line:90%
minus A. Why is it?

00:16:04.340 --> 00:16:08.140 align:middle line:84%
So 0 is an A minus A
over A minus A. It's

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:11.940 align:middle line:90%
a proof of observation two.

00:16:11.940 --> 00:16:14.532 align:middle line:84%
0 is in there because you can
choose these to be the same.

00:16:14.532 --> 00:16:16.240 align:middle line:84%
And you can choose
those to be different.

00:16:16.240 --> 00:16:19.100 align:middle line:90%


00:16:19.100 --> 00:16:22.650 align:middle line:90%
If one is not--

00:16:22.650 --> 00:16:26.000 align:middle line:90%


00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.920 align:middle line:90%
so then we just--

00:16:28.920 --> 00:16:31.740 align:middle line:84%
either everybody in Fp
is in A minus A minus A

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:34.060 align:middle line:90%
minus A or somebody is not.

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:40.590 align:middle line:84%
And so then we take B
plus 1 is the smallest

00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:48.410 align:middle line:84%
number which is not an A minus A
over A minus A. And there we go.

00:16:48.410 --> 00:16:51.710 align:middle line:90%


00:16:51.710 --> 00:16:54.170 align:middle line:84%
And the special thing
that we're using about Fp,

00:16:54.170 --> 00:16:56.888 align:middle line:84%
we've used that we have
the prime field, which

00:16:56.888 --> 00:16:57.930 align:middle line:90%
is just we're using that.

00:16:57.930 --> 00:16:59.733 align:middle line:84%
If you start at 0 and
you keep adding 1,

00:16:59.733 --> 00:17:00.900 align:middle line:90%
you get all of the elements.

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:03.590 align:middle line:90%


00:17:03.590 --> 00:17:05.569 align:middle line:84%
So that's the proof
of observation two.

00:17:05.569 --> 00:17:08.510 align:middle line:90%


00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:11.550 align:middle line:84%
And so now we are
basically done.

00:17:11.550 --> 00:17:16.310 align:middle line:84%
So now we have seen that
if A minus A over A minus A

00:17:16.310 --> 00:17:24.750 align:middle line:84%
is not Fp, then if you take
A and you add this B plus 1.

00:17:24.750 --> 00:17:28.270 align:middle line:84%
So B is an A minus
A over A minus A.

00:17:28.270 --> 00:17:30.270 align:middle line:90%
And I'm going to add 1 to it.

00:17:30.270 --> 00:17:32.630 align:middle line:90%
So B plus 1 is in here.

00:17:32.630 --> 00:17:34.440 align:middle line:90%
There is bigger than A squared.

00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:42.850 align:middle line:90%


00:17:42.850 --> 00:17:48.050 align:middle line:84%
So if I take six elements
of A and I do this,

00:17:48.050 --> 00:17:49.690 align:middle line:84%
the number of different
guys I will get

00:17:49.690 --> 00:17:51.270 align:middle line:90%
is really much bigger then.

00:17:51.270 --> 00:17:54.690 align:middle line:90%


00:17:54.690 --> 00:17:58.710 align:middle line:84%
And then this doesn't
look exactly like my two,

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:01.950 align:middle line:84%
but I just clear the denominator
and expand things out.

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:13.890 align:middle line:90%


00:18:13.890 --> 00:18:15.930 align:middle line:84%
So when I clear the
denominator, I'll

00:18:15.930 --> 00:18:21.050 align:middle line:84%
get A times A minus A
times A from this guy,

00:18:21.050 --> 00:18:23.250 align:middle line:84%
inside of here, I'll
have A minus A plus A

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:27.270 align:middle line:84%
minus A. I'll multiplied by
A. I have a bunch of stuff.

00:18:27.270 --> 00:18:38.380 align:middle line:90%


00:18:38.380 --> 00:18:41.388 align:middle line:84%
So I know-- So that's Katz
and I are old collaborators.

00:18:41.388 --> 00:18:43.180 align:middle line:84%
And I remember talking
with him about this,

00:18:43.180 --> 00:18:48.778 align:middle line:84%
and that it took quite a while
for them to figure out how

00:18:48.778 --> 00:18:50.070 align:middle line:90%
to get started on this problem.

00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:52.660 align:middle line:90%


00:18:52.660 --> 00:18:56.940 align:middle line:84%
Now, looking back at this,
this proof is really clean.

00:18:56.940 --> 00:18:59.380 align:middle line:84%
This lemma is perhaps not--
the statement of the lemma

00:18:59.380 --> 00:19:01.800 align:middle line:84%
is perhaps not the nicest
thing that you might like.

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:10.660 align:middle line:90%


00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:13.780 align:middle line:84%
So there are kind
of cleaner things

00:19:13.780 --> 00:19:15.940 align:middle line:84%
like, for example,
later today, we'll

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:18.540 align:middle line:84%
show that just this
is significantly

00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:23.560 align:middle line:84%
bigger than A and
different variations.

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:36.172 align:middle line:90%


00:19:36.172 --> 00:19:38.110 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we should
mention-- we could ask

00:19:38.110 --> 00:19:40.470 align:middle line:90%
some much simpler questions.

00:19:40.470 --> 00:19:45.310 align:middle line:84%
We could just say if you
have a subset of Fp called A,

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:51.030 align:middle line:84%
is it true that A plus A is
always much bigger than A?

00:19:51.030 --> 00:19:53.870 align:middle line:84%
That's true for most
subsets, but it's not

00:19:53.870 --> 00:19:55.870 align:middle line:90%
true for all of them.

00:19:55.870 --> 00:19:59.830 align:middle line:84%
But thinking about that much
simpler question is actually--

00:19:59.830 --> 00:20:03.650 align:middle line:84%
so that's foundational question
in additive combinatorics,

00:20:03.650 --> 00:20:06.510 align:middle line:84%
to understand that,
and understanding

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:11.080 align:middle line:84%
that well feeds into being able
to understand this stuff better.

00:20:11.080 --> 00:20:12.830 align:middle line:84%
So let me pose this
on the board and we'll

00:20:12.830 --> 00:20:14.010 align:middle line:90%
start to talk about it.

00:20:14.010 --> 00:20:20.750 align:middle line:90%


00:20:20.750 --> 00:20:30.960 align:middle line:84%
So my question for us is
when is A plus A small?

00:20:30.960 --> 00:20:35.210 align:middle line:90%


00:20:35.210 --> 00:20:38.610 align:middle line:84%
So here I have in mind
that A is a subset of Fp,

00:20:38.610 --> 00:20:41.570 align:middle line:84%
although we could have a very
similar conversation if was

00:20:41.570 --> 00:20:46.030 align:middle line:84%
a subset of E or was A
subset of R or dot, dot, dot.

00:20:46.030 --> 00:20:49.450 align:middle line:90%


00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:52.530 align:middle line:84%
Can anybody think
of a subset of Fp

00:20:52.530 --> 00:21:05.650 align:middle line:84%
where A plus A is only a
tiny bit bigger than A. Yeah?

00:21:05.650 --> 00:21:12.530 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: A is some
set of [INAUDIBLE] that

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:17.090 align:middle line:84%
includes numbers and the
negative values of those numbers

00:21:17.090 --> 00:21:22.130 align:middle line:84%
in Fp, like only one
negative 1, two negative 2,

00:21:22.130 --> 00:21:25.250 align:middle line:90%
or something like that?

00:21:25.250 --> 00:21:25.917 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:21:25.917 --> 00:21:28.000 align:middle line:84%
So the comment is maybe I
should have some numbers

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:29.270 align:middle line:90%
and negative in those numbers.

00:21:29.270 --> 00:21:31.200 align:middle line:84%
Let me ask you a more
precise question.

00:21:31.200 --> 00:21:34.100 align:middle line:84%
So you have to choose
L numbers in Fp,

00:21:34.100 --> 00:21:35.860 align:middle line:84%
and you want to
choose them to make

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:38.135 align:middle line:90%
A plus A as small as possible.

00:21:38.135 --> 00:21:39.010 align:middle line:90%
Who would you choose?

00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:43.620 align:middle line:90%


00:21:43.620 --> 00:21:44.515 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:21:44.515 --> 00:21:47.222 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Could be an
arithmetic [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:47.222 --> 00:21:49.180 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, you
could choose an arithmetic

00:21:49.180 --> 00:21:50.740 align:middle line:90%
progression.

00:21:50.740 --> 00:21:59.140 align:middle line:84%
So example one-- suppose A was
just the numbers from 1 up to L.

00:21:59.140 --> 00:22:04.020 align:middle line:84%
So A plus A will be the
numbers from negative 2 to 2L.

00:22:04.020 --> 00:22:08.500 align:middle line:84%
So A plus A is at
most 2 times A.

00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:10.640 align:middle line:84%
It's the tiniest
bit less than that,

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:12.900 align:middle line:84%
but not very important
for our discussion.

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:19.060 align:middle line:84%
And this is the smallest that
A plus A could possibly be.

00:22:19.060 --> 00:22:22.120 align:middle line:84%
And it doesn't have
to be one up to L.

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:25.660 align:middle line:84%
It would work just as well if it
was an arithmetic progression.

00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:29.150 align:middle line:90%
So example one prime--

00:22:29.150 --> 00:22:39.737 align:middle line:84%
our set A is little a plus nd,
where n goes from 1 up to L.

00:22:39.737 --> 00:22:41.570 align:middle line:84%
And then if you think
about it a little bit,

00:22:41.570 --> 00:22:43.730 align:middle line:84%
the size of the subset
behaves just the same.

00:22:43.730 --> 00:22:55.790 align:middle line:90%


00:22:55.790 --> 00:22:58.390 align:middle line:84%
There's another example
that's a little bit more

00:22:58.390 --> 00:23:00.030 align:middle line:90%
general than this.

00:23:00.030 --> 00:23:01.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is an
arithmetic progression

00:23:01.590 --> 00:23:03.690 align:middle line:84%
where you have just
one kind of difference.

00:23:03.690 --> 00:23:07.590 align:middle line:90%


00:23:07.590 --> 00:23:12.110 align:middle line:90%
And you could have something--

00:23:12.110 --> 00:23:16.910 align:middle line:84%
so you could visualize
it like this.

00:23:16.910 --> 00:23:19.150 align:middle line:84%
And you could have
a similar thing

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:25.870 align:middle line:84%
involving a two-dimensional grid
or a higher-dimensional grid.

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:30.330 align:middle line:84%
So example two is
that A is a plus n1

00:23:30.330 --> 00:23:43.170 align:middle line:84%
d1 plus dot, dot, dot plus nr dr
where ni goes from 1 up to Li.

00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:48.570 align:middle line:90%


00:23:48.570 --> 00:23:51.610 align:middle line:84%
So what happens when
you take A plus A?

00:23:51.610 --> 00:23:58.070 align:middle line:84%
It is contained in 2a
plus n1 d1 plus dot, dot,

00:23:58.070 --> 00:24:03.760 align:middle line:84%
dot plus nr dr where, now,
the ni go in between 2 and 2L.

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:09.370 align:middle line:90%


00:24:09.370 --> 00:24:12.570 align:middle line:90%
And so we see from this--

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:15.810 align:middle line:90%
well, which is contained in--

00:24:15.810 --> 00:24:17.810 align:middle line:90%
I could put a 1.

00:24:17.810 --> 00:24:22.630 align:middle line:84%
So it's contained in something
that is 2 to the r times bigger.

00:24:22.630 --> 00:24:29.980 align:middle line:84%
So we get A plus A is bounded
by 2 to the r times A.

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:33.100 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is called
a generalized arithmetic

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:34.180 align:middle line:90%
progression.

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:37.420 align:middle line:84%
It has a dimension,
little r, and it

00:24:37.420 --> 00:24:43.070 align:middle line:84%
has a volume or cardinality,
which is L1 up to Lr.

00:24:43.070 --> 00:24:59.860 align:middle line:90%


00:24:59.860 --> 00:25:01.320 align:middle line:90%
Can anybody think of any others?

00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:09.020 align:middle line:90%


00:25:09.020 --> 00:25:11.120 align:middle line:84%
So it is hard to
think of other ones.

00:25:11.120 --> 00:25:12.860 align:middle line:84%
And in some sense,
and depending on how

00:25:12.860 --> 00:25:17.340 align:middle line:84%
we quantify it a little bit,
these sets or maybe these sets

00:25:17.340 --> 00:25:20.220 align:middle line:84%
and their close cousins appear
to be the only sets that

00:25:20.220 --> 00:25:22.580 align:middle line:90%
have a really small subset.

00:25:22.580 --> 00:25:26.080 align:middle line:84%
And this was investigated
by Freiman starting

00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:30.308 align:middle line:84%
in the '60s and '70s, and he
proved a theorem to that effect

00:25:30.308 --> 00:25:31.350 align:middle line:90%
called Freiman's theorem.

00:25:31.350 --> 00:25:35.620 align:middle line:90%


00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:41.100 align:middle line:84%
And this is a cornerstone
of additive combinatorics.

00:25:41.100 --> 00:25:47.200 align:middle line:90%


00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:50.660 align:middle line:84%
Freiman's proof was
somewhat difficult to read,

00:25:50.660 --> 00:25:53.060 align:middle line:84%
and Ruzsa thought a lot
about it and clarified it.

00:25:53.060 --> 00:25:56.360 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
now called usually

00:25:56.360 --> 00:25:57.670 align:middle line:90%
the Freiman-Ruzsa theorem.

00:25:57.670 --> 00:26:04.280 align:middle line:90%


00:26:04.280 --> 00:26:07.320 align:middle line:90%
So it says the following thing--

00:26:07.320 --> 00:26:17.000 align:middle line:90%
says that if A is in Z--

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.200 align:middle line:84%
the same thing would
be true in Z mod p--

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:25.850 align:middle line:84%
and A plus A is less
than or equal to KA,

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:35.210 align:middle line:84%
then A is contained in a gap
with dimension little r that

00:26:35.210 --> 00:26:41.450 align:middle line:84%
only depends on K
and volume at most

00:26:41.450 --> 00:26:49.570 align:middle line:84%
V. That only depends on
K times the size of A.

00:26:49.570 --> 00:26:52.430 align:middle line:84%
So it roughly says that
if A plus A is small,

00:26:52.430 --> 00:26:54.410 align:middle line:84%
it is because a
resembles example

00:26:54.410 --> 00:26:58.170 align:middle line:84%
two, which is a
generalization of example one.

00:26:58.170 --> 00:27:00.770 align:middle line:84%
So in some sense these
are the only sets that

00:27:00.770 --> 00:27:02.060 align:middle line:90%
have a really small subset.

00:27:02.060 --> 00:27:04.650 align:middle line:90%


00:27:04.650 --> 00:27:08.750 align:middle line:84%
So this is an important theorem
in additive combinatorics.

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:11.010 align:middle line:84%
But there are two
caveats about it.

00:27:11.010 --> 00:27:14.130 align:middle line:84%
So one caveat is that it's
a pretty deep theorem,

00:27:14.130 --> 00:27:17.250 align:middle line:90%
where the proof is substantial.

00:27:17.250 --> 00:27:21.560 align:middle line:84%
And the other caveat is that the
quantitative bounds are weak.

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:27.100 align:middle line:90%


00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:34.580 align:middle line:84%
So in the original version,
r of K was quite large.

00:27:34.580 --> 00:27:40.660 align:middle line:84%
So r of K was something like
x of K to a power and V of K

00:27:40.660 --> 00:27:45.210 align:middle line:84%
was even larger, so xp
of x of K to a power.

00:27:45.210 --> 00:27:51.876 align:middle line:90%


00:27:51.876 --> 00:27:59.180 align:middle line:84%
Now it is a trivial fact
that any set A is contained

00:27:59.180 --> 00:28:02.060 align:middle line:84%
in a generalized arithmetic
progression of dimension

00:28:02.060 --> 00:28:07.860 align:middle line:84%
equal to the size of A. So this
is only interesting if r of K

00:28:07.860 --> 00:28:15.140 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than the size of A.
So this was only interesting,

00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:21.380 align:middle line:84%
only meaningful, let's
say, if k was quite small.

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:27.240 align:middle line:90%


00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:31.000 align:middle line:84%
There is a big goal in
additive combinatorics

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:32.760 align:middle line:84%
to improve the
quantitative bounds

00:28:32.760 --> 00:28:37.120 align:middle line:90%
in Friedman's theorem, and.

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:41.000 align:middle line:84%
one benchmark is a conjecture
called the polynomial frame

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:44.280 align:middle line:84%
in Ruzsa conjecture, which would
say something meaningful even

00:28:44.280 --> 00:28:46.840 align:middle line:90%
if K was a small power of A.

00:28:46.840 --> 00:28:50.480 align:middle line:84%
So there's a
conjecture that they

00:28:50.480 --> 00:28:57.080 align:middle line:84%
would have a
meaningful bound if K

00:28:57.080 --> 00:29:06.600 align:middle line:84%
is A to the delta for some
small but universal delta

00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:09.720 align:middle line:90%
bigger than 0.

00:29:09.720 --> 00:29:11.660 align:middle line:84%
And this is still
an open conjecture.

00:29:11.660 --> 00:29:13.760 align:middle line:84%
So it's out of range,
maybe only a little

00:29:13.760 --> 00:29:18.530 align:middle line:84%
out of range of
current techniques.

00:29:18.530 --> 00:29:22.490 align:middle line:84%
But if K was, say, I
don't know, A to the 0.1,

00:29:22.490 --> 00:29:25.370 align:middle line:84%
all this stuff about
Freiman's theorem,

00:29:25.370 --> 00:29:28.640 align:middle line:84%
we are very far from being
able to deal with that.

00:29:28.640 --> 00:29:32.650 align:middle line:90%


00:29:32.650 --> 00:29:36.450 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you look at Freiman's
theorem, what we're trying to do

00:29:36.450 --> 00:29:40.850 align:middle line:84%
is to give a complete
classification of all the sets a

00:29:40.850 --> 00:29:42.650 align:middle line:90%
that do this.

00:29:42.650 --> 00:29:45.010 align:middle line:84%
And the complete
classification is

00:29:45.010 --> 00:29:49.090 align:middle line:84%
something we only understand
if K is really, really small.

00:29:49.090 --> 00:29:50.610 align:middle line:84%
But you could also
ask for something

00:29:50.610 --> 00:29:53.770 align:middle line:84%
which is not as strong as
a complete classification,

00:29:53.770 --> 00:29:56.210 align:middle line:84%
but just some kind of
interesting information

00:29:56.210 --> 00:29:58.100 align:middle line:90%
about sets with small subset.

00:29:58.100 --> 00:30:00.650 align:middle line:90%


00:30:00.650 --> 00:30:05.090 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at
this example, you'll

00:30:05.090 --> 00:30:08.310 align:middle line:84%
notice that not only
it has small subset,

00:30:08.310 --> 00:30:12.250 align:middle line:84%
but it has also small
a bunch of other stuff.

00:30:12.250 --> 00:30:14.650 align:middle line:84%
In these examples,
A plus A is small.

00:30:14.650 --> 00:30:16.740 align:middle line:90%
Also, A minus A is small.

00:30:16.740 --> 00:30:18.810 align:middle line:90%
Also, A plus A plus A is small.

00:30:18.810 --> 00:30:22.100 align:middle line:90%


00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:27.840 align:middle line:84%
And for those things, we
have much simpler proofs,

00:30:27.840 --> 00:30:30.540 align:middle line:84%
and the quantitative
bounds are much better.

00:30:30.540 --> 00:30:33.740 align:middle line:84%
And they come from some
lemmas that I think originally

00:30:33.740 --> 00:30:37.380 align:middle line:84%
were designed as
lemmas for this theorem

00:30:37.380 --> 00:30:39.880 align:middle line:84%
but which have lots of
independent applications.

00:30:39.880 --> 00:30:46.556 align:middle line:90%


00:30:46.556 --> 00:30:50.120 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem, I don't
plan to prove in the class,

00:30:50.120 --> 00:30:52.640 align:middle line:84%
but I wanted to mention
it for historical context.

00:30:52.640 --> 00:30:55.460 align:middle line:84%
And these lemmas
are really important

00:30:55.460 --> 00:30:58.860 align:middle line:84%
and have reasonable short
proofs and, I think,

00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:02.200 align:middle line:84%
are worth for a wide range
of people knowing about them.

00:31:02.200 --> 00:31:18.832 align:middle line:90%


00:31:18.832 --> 00:31:22.880 align:middle line:84%
So the first of the lemmas
is called the Ruzsa triangle

00:31:22.880 --> 00:31:23.740 align:middle line:90%
inequality.

00:31:23.740 --> 00:31:29.920 align:middle line:90%


00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:39.000 align:middle line:84%
So it says if Z is an abelian
group, and A and B and C

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:47.560 align:middle line:84%
are subsets of Z, then size of
A times the size of B minus C

00:31:47.560 --> 00:31:52.000 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by the size of A
minus B times the size of A

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:57.640 align:middle line:90%
minus C.

00:31:57.640 --> 00:32:01.480 align:middle line:84%
So this might take
a little digesting.

00:32:01.480 --> 00:32:05.320 align:middle line:84%
All of these letters feels a
little bit like alphabet soup.

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:08.882 align:middle line:84%
The fact that we can
put three different sets

00:32:08.882 --> 00:32:10.340 align:middle line:84%
makes it a little
harder to digest.

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:13.420 align:middle line:84%
But, of course, it makes it
more flexible in general.

00:32:13.420 --> 00:32:16.430 align:middle line:84%
And by plugging in different
choices for these three sets,

00:32:16.430 --> 00:32:18.370 align:middle line:84%
you can prove some
simpler things.

00:32:18.370 --> 00:32:20.180 align:middle line:84%
Let me illustrate
this with an example.

00:32:20.180 --> 00:32:23.130 align:middle line:90%


00:32:23.130 --> 00:32:26.530 align:middle line:84%
As a corollary of
this, we will see

00:32:26.530 --> 00:32:30.460 align:middle line:84%
that if the sum set is small,
then the difference set is also

00:32:30.460 --> 00:32:30.960 align:middle line:90%
small.

00:32:30.960 --> 00:32:43.650 align:middle line:90%


00:32:43.650 --> 00:32:55.010 align:middle line:84%
So corollary-- if A plus A
is smaller than K times A,

00:32:55.010 --> 00:33:04.530 align:middle line:84%
then A minus A is smaller than
K squared K squared times L.

00:33:04.530 --> 00:33:06.370 align:middle line:84%
So this lemma is
meaningful as long

00:33:06.370 --> 00:33:10.250 align:middle line:84%
as K is slightly smaller
than the square root of A.

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:16.180 align:middle line:84%
So in a much wider range than
the Freiman-Ruzsa theorem.

00:33:16.180 --> 00:33:19.460 align:middle line:90%
This is a meaningful statement.

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:23.360 align:middle line:84%
So proof-- we're just
going to use Ruzsa,

00:33:23.360 --> 00:33:25.900 align:middle line:84%
and I have to tell you
who are A and B and C.

00:33:25.900 --> 00:33:31.010 align:middle line:84%
So A will be A. And
then I think B--

00:33:31.010 --> 00:33:36.860 align:middle line:90%


00:33:36.860 --> 00:33:37.560 align:middle line:90%
let me see.

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:40.900 align:middle line:90%


00:33:40.900 --> 00:33:50.900 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, B and C are both negative
A. So if you look at B minus C,

00:33:50.900 --> 00:33:52.160 align:middle line:90%
there's a lot of minus signs.

00:33:52.160 --> 00:33:53.618 align:middle line:84%
This is a little
bit silly looking.

00:33:53.618 --> 00:34:00.580 align:middle line:90%


00:34:00.580 --> 00:34:10.213 align:middle line:84%
So that's just A minus A.
And A minus B or A minus C--

00:34:10.213 --> 00:34:11.880 align:middle line:84%
they're the same as
each other because B

00:34:11.880 --> 00:34:19.920 align:middle line:84%
is the same as C. That's A minus
negative A. So that's A plus A.

00:34:19.920 --> 00:34:22.679 align:middle line:84%
So now if we just
plug in Ruzsa, it

00:34:22.679 --> 00:34:27.199 align:middle line:84%
says A times this
guy, A minus A,

00:34:27.199 --> 00:34:30.679 align:middle line:84%
is less than this
guy times this guy.

00:34:30.679 --> 00:34:34.040 align:middle line:90%
That's A plus A squared.

00:34:34.040 --> 00:34:36.360 align:middle line:84%
And by hypothesis,
that's smaller

00:34:36.360 --> 00:34:40.480 align:middle line:90%
than K squared A squared.

00:34:40.480 --> 00:34:43.139 align:middle line:84%
And if you cancel the
factor of A, that's it.

00:34:43.139 --> 00:35:00.280 align:middle line:90%


00:35:00.280 --> 00:35:03.880 align:middle line:84%
And this has a very simple proof
that will fit on this board

00:35:03.880 --> 00:35:06.800 align:middle line:84%
and which already says something
interesting and nontrivial

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:10.210 align:middle line:84%
about how sums and differences
and stuff fit together.

00:35:10.210 --> 00:35:12.250 align:middle line:90%
So here's the proof.

00:35:12.250 --> 00:35:20.890 align:middle line:84%
We will construct a map phi
that goes from A cross B minus C

00:35:20.890 --> 00:35:26.510 align:middle line:84%
into A minus B cross A
minus C, which is injective.

00:35:26.510 --> 00:35:30.330 align:middle line:90%


00:35:30.330 --> 00:35:32.470 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
cardinality of this set.

00:35:32.470 --> 00:35:34.810 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
cardinality of that set.

00:35:34.810 --> 00:35:37.690 align:middle line:84%
And the reason that this
set is bigger than that set

00:35:37.690 --> 00:35:41.890 align:middle line:84%
is that we have an injection
from one end to the other.

00:35:41.890 --> 00:35:44.610 align:middle line:90%
How does the injection work?

00:35:44.610 --> 00:35:49.310 align:middle line:84%
For every d in B minus
C, we can choose--

00:35:49.310 --> 00:35:51.330 align:middle line:84%
so by definition,
this d can be written

00:35:51.330 --> 00:35:55.090 align:middle line:84%
as somebody in B minus
somebody in C. Let's pick them.

00:35:55.090 --> 00:36:01.210 align:middle line:84%
We choose B of d
and B C of d and C

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:07.290 align:middle line:90%
so that d is B of d minus C of d

00:36:07.290 --> 00:36:10.390 align:middle line:90%
Now, what's our map?

00:36:10.390 --> 00:36:12.630 align:middle line:90%
Phi takes an A and a d.

00:36:12.630 --> 00:36:15.190 align:middle line:90%
A lives here, and d lives there.

00:36:15.190 --> 00:36:17.750 align:middle line:84%
We need to output
somebody an A minus

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:26.670 align:middle line:84%
so we take A minus B of d
and then A minus C of d.

00:36:26.670 --> 00:36:30.070 align:middle line:84%
So that is a map
from here to here.

00:36:30.070 --> 00:36:33.630 align:middle line:90%
Why is it injective?

00:36:33.630 --> 00:36:42.230 align:middle line:84%
So to check that
it's injective, we're

00:36:42.230 --> 00:36:49.790 align:middle line:84%
going to suppose that phi
of A d is given to us as xy.

00:36:49.790 --> 00:37:00.630 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to
find A and d from x and y

00:37:00.630 --> 00:37:02.040 align:middle line:90%
and from this choice.

00:37:02.040 --> 00:37:11.920 align:middle line:90%


00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:13.880 align:middle line:84%
So the choice we made,
once and for all, we

00:37:13.880 --> 00:37:15.560 align:middle line:90%
used it to build the map.

00:37:15.560 --> 00:37:19.040 align:middle line:84%
And now we have to prove that
there's only one A and d that

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:22.400 align:middle line:90%
give a certain x and y here.

00:37:22.400 --> 00:37:24.720 align:middle line:90%
So how do we recover them?

00:37:24.720 --> 00:37:30.440 align:middle line:84%
Well, if this is
x and this is y,

00:37:30.440 --> 00:37:38.280 align:middle line:84%
let me see that y minus x is B
of d minus C of d, which is d.

00:37:38.280 --> 00:37:41.560 align:middle line:90%
So that's how we find d.

00:37:41.560 --> 00:37:44.360 align:middle line:84%
And once we find d,
it's easy to find--

00:37:44.360 --> 00:37:46.980 align:middle line:84%
once we find d, then we
know B of d and C of d,

00:37:46.980 --> 00:37:56.080 align:middle line:84%
and now it's easy to find
A. So x minus x plus B of d

00:37:56.080 --> 00:38:02.540 align:middle line:90%
is A. It's very short.

00:38:02.540 --> 00:38:07.130 align:middle line:84%
It feels a teeny bit
like a magic trick to me.

00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:08.910 align:middle line:84%
But on this board
and this board,

00:38:08.910 --> 00:38:11.230 align:middle line:84%
we have seen that if
the sum set is small,

00:38:11.230 --> 00:38:12.860 align:middle line:84%
then the difference
set is also small.

00:38:12.860 --> 00:38:23.010 align:middle line:90%


00:38:23.010 --> 00:38:25.170 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:38:25.170 --> 00:38:34.610 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Take the log, you get
something that looks exactly

00:38:34.610 --> 00:38:37.470 align:middle line:84%
like a triangle inequality
is there any way

00:38:37.470 --> 00:38:41.930 align:middle line:90%
to see that it's [INAUDIBLE]?

00:38:41.930 --> 00:38:47.290 align:middle line:90%


00:38:47.290 --> 00:38:50.170 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so the
question is it's called triangle

00:38:50.170 --> 00:38:51.070 align:middle line:90%
inequality.

00:38:51.070 --> 00:38:54.350 align:middle line:84%
And it looks like if we take the
logarithm and play with this,

00:38:54.350 --> 00:38:56.790 align:middle line:84%
then something will look
like the triangle inequality.

00:38:56.790 --> 00:39:00.030 align:middle line:90%


00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:02.870 align:middle line:84%
So Ruzsa did have that in mind
when he named it that way.

00:39:02.870 --> 00:39:07.270 align:middle line:84%
So he produced a pseudodistance
between different sets,

00:39:07.270 --> 00:39:10.030 align:middle line:84%
say, between A and B
or B and C or whatever.

00:39:10.030 --> 00:39:15.870 align:middle line:84%
And this translates into saying
that the Ruzsa pseudodistance

00:39:15.870 --> 00:39:17.410 align:middle line:90%
obeys the triangle inequality.

00:39:17.410 --> 00:39:20.270 align:middle line:84%
The distance from B to C is
bounded by the distance from A

00:39:20.270 --> 00:39:24.790 align:middle line:84%
to B plus the different distance
from B to A plus the distance

00:39:24.790 --> 00:39:27.990 align:middle line:90%
from A to C.

00:39:27.990 --> 00:39:33.190 align:middle line:84%
I'm not sure whether
that is helpful or not.

00:39:33.190 --> 00:39:35.030 align:middle line:84%
Pseudodistance is
a little bit funny.

00:39:35.030 --> 00:39:38.310 align:middle line:84%
It's not true that the
distance from A to itself is 0.

00:39:38.310 --> 00:39:42.110 align:middle line:84%
So it's not quite like
distances that I'm used to.

00:39:42.110 --> 00:39:44.560 align:middle line:84%
So that intuition, may
or may not be helpful.

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:49.190 align:middle line:90%


00:39:49.190 --> 00:39:51.270 align:middle line:84%
I guess we will see tomorrow
that, sometimes, you

00:39:51.270 --> 00:39:53.270 align:middle line:90%
use this many times.

00:39:53.270 --> 00:39:55.510 align:middle line:84%
How would you use the
triangle inequality?

00:39:55.510 --> 00:39:58.190 align:middle line:84%
Well, the distance
from A to Z is

00:39:58.190 --> 00:40:00.510 align:middle line:84%
bounded by the distance from
A to B plus the distance

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:02.350 align:middle line:84%
from B to C plus the
distance from C to D,

00:40:02.350 --> 00:40:04.642 align:middle line:84%
duh, duh, duh, duh, duh, and
maybe each of those things

00:40:04.642 --> 00:40:05.820 align:middle line:90%
is easier to understand.

00:40:05.820 --> 00:40:08.320 align:middle line:84%
And by the triangle inequality,
we can put them together.

00:40:08.320 --> 00:40:11.880 align:middle line:84%
So you can use this
inequality in that way.

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:14.110 align:middle line:90%
And we'll see that tomorrow--

00:40:14.110 --> 00:40:14.610 align:middle line:90%
Thursday.

00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:16.997 align:middle line:90%


00:40:16.997 --> 00:40:18.330 align:middle line:90%
Any other questions or comments?

00:40:18.330 --> 00:40:22.040 align:middle line:90%


00:40:22.040 --> 00:40:28.920 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can I ask about
the movie denominator trick?

00:40:28.920 --> 00:40:33.280 align:middle line:84%
Just not sure how
that worked out.

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:36.420 align:middle line:84%
Does it require something
nontrivial like this?

00:40:36.420 --> 00:40:39.458 align:middle line:90%


00:40:39.458 --> 00:40:42.000 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: The question is about
the removing the denominator

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:42.960 align:middle line:90%
trick?

00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:49.200 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you
use that [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:49.200 --> 00:40:51.720 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Like when we had an
A minus A in the denominator

00:40:51.720 --> 00:40:53.960 align:middle line:90%
and we multiplied it out?

00:40:53.960 --> 00:40:58.020 align:middle line:90%
So that was just algebra.

00:40:58.020 --> 00:41:01.990 align:middle line:90%


00:41:01.990 --> 00:41:04.670 align:middle line:84%
It's not something
fancy like this.

00:41:04.670 --> 00:41:08.617 align:middle line:90%


00:41:08.617 --> 00:41:09.450 align:middle line:90%
Let me bracket that.

00:41:09.450 --> 00:41:11.117 align:middle line:84%
We'll see a little
later, something else

00:41:11.117 --> 00:41:12.770 align:middle line:90%
with removing denominators.

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:14.550 align:middle line:90%
And let's come back to it then.

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:21.130 align:middle line:90%


00:41:21.130 --> 00:41:24.370 align:middle line:84%
Do you think-- did I
understand your question or--

00:41:24.370 --> 00:41:30.830 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I'm just not
sure how that [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:30.830 --> 00:41:33.730 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: You only
need 6 instead of 8

00:41:33.730 --> 00:41:34.770 align:middle line:90%
because that's the--

00:41:34.770 --> 00:41:39.630 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, let's check in
about it at the end of class.

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:43.090 align:middle line:84%
The other important
lemma from this field

00:41:43.090 --> 00:41:45.170 align:middle line:84%
that went into the proof
of Freiman's theorem

00:41:45.170 --> 00:41:47.070 align:middle line:90%
is called Plunnecke inequality.

00:41:47.070 --> 00:41:54.850 align:middle line:90%


00:41:54.850 --> 00:41:57.050 align:middle line:84%
Plunnecke inequality
allows us to say things

00:41:57.050 --> 00:42:00.810 align:middle line:84%
like if A plus A is small,
then A plus A plus A is small.

00:42:00.810 --> 00:42:10.550 align:middle line:90%


00:42:10.550 --> 00:42:19.430 align:middle line:84%
So if A and B are subsets
of Z, an abelian group,

00:42:19.430 --> 00:42:25.540 align:middle line:84%
and A plus B is bounded
by K times A, then--

00:42:25.540 --> 00:42:28.390 align:middle line:90%


00:42:28.390 --> 00:42:30.470 align:middle line:90%
let me make a little notation.

00:42:30.470 --> 00:42:36.710 align:middle line:84%
So sometimes, we might want to
talk about B plus B many times.

00:42:36.710 --> 00:42:39.390 align:middle line:90%
So let's say this is n times.

00:42:39.390 --> 00:42:42.510 align:middle line:84%
This is sometimes
written as n times B,

00:42:42.510 --> 00:42:46.230 align:middle line:84%
although I feel like that
is slightly confusing.

00:42:46.230 --> 00:42:52.640 align:middle line:84%
So I've decided to adopt this
notation, B some n times.

00:42:52.640 --> 00:42:56.070 align:middle line:90%


00:42:56.070 --> 00:43:04.360 align:middle line:84%
So I could take B plus m
times minus B plus n times,

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:12.720 align:middle line:84%
and that's bounded by K
to the m plus n times A.

00:43:12.720 --> 00:43:17.320 align:middle line:84%
So let's do a few
corollaries of this.

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:19.920 align:middle line:84%
So just by plugging
in A equals B,

00:43:19.920 --> 00:43:26.400 align:middle line:84%
we see that if A plus A is
less than or equal to KA,

00:43:26.400 --> 00:43:31.680 align:middle line:84%
then A minus A is
less than K squared A.

00:43:31.680 --> 00:43:34.200 align:middle line:84%
That's actually the
corollary we already proved.

00:43:34.200 --> 00:43:37.520 align:middle line:84%
But also, we could
say A plus A plus A

00:43:37.520 --> 00:43:45.720 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by K cubed A. I'm
just plugging in A equals B,

00:43:45.720 --> 00:43:48.240 align:middle line:90%
and this is m is 3 and n is 0.

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:52.120 align:middle line:84%
And you can see you can
put higher powers here.

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:54.560 align:middle line:84%
Also another
corollary we can get

00:43:54.560 --> 00:43:56.860 align:middle line:84%
is we can switch the
role of these guys

00:43:56.860 --> 00:43:58.580 align:middle line:90%
in the first corollary.

00:43:58.580 --> 00:44:04.500 align:middle line:84%
So we can say if A
minus A is small,

00:44:04.500 --> 00:44:06.650 align:middle line:90%
then A plus A is also small.

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:10.700 align:middle line:90%


00:44:10.700 --> 00:44:18.300 align:middle line:84%
So proof is that B is negative
A. So this is A plus B.

00:44:18.300 --> 00:44:50.780 align:middle line:84%
And then this is
basically B plus B.

00:44:50.780 --> 00:44:52.860 align:middle line:90%
We can also use this.

00:44:52.860 --> 00:44:54.000 align:middle line:90%
So we'll prove this.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:55.870 align:middle line:84%
That will be our last
big goal of the class.

00:44:55.870 --> 00:44:59.710 align:middle line:90%


00:44:59.710 --> 00:45:01.990 align:middle line:84%
So this Ruzsa inequality
and Plunnecke inequality

00:45:01.990 --> 00:45:03.210 align:middle line:90%
have many, many uses.

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:06.550 align:middle line:84%
And one simple use is we can
use it to clean up and improve

00:45:06.550 --> 00:45:08.990 align:middle line:84%
the statement of
our lemma that Fp

00:45:08.990 --> 00:45:12.630 align:middle line:84%
has no quantitative
approximate subfields.

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:14.625 align:middle line:84%
So let me recall what
we proved so far,

00:45:14.625 --> 00:45:16.250 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll improve
it a little bit.

00:45:16.250 --> 00:45:25.790 align:middle line:90%


00:45:25.790 --> 00:45:33.630 align:middle line:84%
So lemma one was
if A is in Fp, then

00:45:33.630 --> 00:45:45.230 align:middle line:84%
either A minus A over
A minus A is all of Fp

00:45:45.230 --> 00:45:51.810 align:middle line:90%
or A times A minus A times A--

00:45:51.810 --> 00:45:53.290 align:middle line:90%
so now I can write this better.

00:45:53.290 --> 00:45:58.520 align:middle line:84%
We have three or four of
those minus three or four

00:45:58.520 --> 00:46:04.160 align:middle line:90%
of those A squared.

00:46:04.160 --> 00:46:07.240 align:middle line:84%
So we can improve
this in a way that you

00:46:07.240 --> 00:46:09.840 align:middle line:84%
don't need to have so many
different expressions floating

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:11.120 align:middle line:90%
around.

00:46:11.120 --> 00:46:16.280 align:middle line:84%
So we can say that if A
is in Fp and the size of A

00:46:16.280 --> 00:46:20.880 align:middle line:84%
is p to the S, where S
is strictly less than 1,

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:26.240 align:middle line:84%
then the size of A
times A minus A times A

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:33.012 align:middle line:84%
is at least p to the S plus
epsilon of S. And here,

00:46:33.012 --> 00:46:34.470 align:middle line:84%
you could put either
plus or minus.

00:46:34.470 --> 00:46:38.840 align:middle line:90%


00:46:38.840 --> 00:46:43.400 align:middle line:84%
And this epsilon of
S is bigger than 0.

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:44.740 align:middle line:90%
So again, it's continuous.

00:46:44.740 --> 00:46:45.640 align:middle line:90%
It's explicit.

00:46:45.640 --> 00:46:48.190 align:middle line:84%
But it's a little bit messy,
and it's a little bit small.

00:46:48.190 --> 00:46:50.760 align:middle line:90%


00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:53.060 align:middle line:84%
You take any subset which
is significantly smaller

00:46:53.060 --> 00:46:58.000 align:middle line:84%
than the whole field, if you
take A times A minus A times A,

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.320 align:middle line:84%
it will be significantly
bigger than you started with.

00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:06.900 align:middle line:90%


00:47:06.900 --> 00:47:09.167 align:middle line:84%
So if you just took
A minus A, that

00:47:09.167 --> 00:47:11.500 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't be good enough because
A could be an arithmetic

00:47:11.500 --> 00:47:13.400 align:middle line:90%
progression.

00:47:13.400 --> 00:47:15.300 align:middle line:84%
So that might have almost
the same size as A.

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:17.380 align:middle line:84%
If you just took A
times A, that wouldn't

00:47:17.380 --> 00:47:22.020 align:middle line:84%
be good enough, because A could
be a geometric progression--

00:47:22.020 --> 00:47:26.500 align:middle line:84%
2 to the 1, 2 to the
2, up to 2 to the L.

00:47:26.500 --> 00:47:29.840 align:middle line:84%
But if you take both
sums and products,

00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:32.540 align:middle line:84%
then you have to end up with
significantly more stuff

00:47:32.540 --> 00:47:34.740 align:middle line:90%
than you started with.

00:47:34.740 --> 00:47:36.903 align:middle line:84%
So that's why this is
called sum-product theory.

00:47:36.903 --> 00:47:38.820 align:middle line:84%
If you have both sums
and products interacting

00:47:38.820 --> 00:47:43.020 align:middle line:84%
with each other, then
something happens.

00:47:43.020 --> 00:47:58.590 align:middle line:84%
So proof-- so there are two
cases, case 1 and case 2.

00:47:58.590 --> 00:48:00.340 align:middle line:84%
But I'm actually going
to do case 2 first.

00:48:00.340 --> 00:48:12.270 align:middle line:90%


00:48:12.270 --> 00:48:16.950 align:middle line:84%
So it could be that A times A
is already much bigger than A.

00:48:16.950 --> 00:48:18.990 align:middle line:90%
Then we just declare victory.

00:48:18.990 --> 00:48:25.510 align:middle line:84%
So if A times A is bigger than
A to the plus delta and we

00:48:25.510 --> 00:48:26.570 align:middle line:90%
declare victory.

00:48:26.570 --> 00:48:28.960 align:middle line:84%
And here, delta is going to
be much smaller than epsilon.

00:48:28.960 --> 00:48:34.270 align:middle line:90%


00:48:34.270 --> 00:48:35.790 align:middle line:90%
Or maybe we could say that.

00:48:35.790 --> 00:48:47.710 align:middle line:90%


00:48:47.710 --> 00:48:53.640 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, A times A is
basically the same size as A.

00:48:53.640 --> 00:49:02.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, if A times A plus A
times A is much bigger than A,

00:49:02.560 --> 00:49:03.670 align:middle line:90%
then we declare victory.

00:49:03.670 --> 00:49:09.120 align:middle line:90%


00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:10.020 align:middle line:90%
Wait a second.

00:49:10.020 --> 00:49:10.520 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, here.

00:49:10.520 --> 00:49:15.420 align:middle line:84%
I guess let's just
put this right here.

00:49:15.420 --> 00:49:23.880 align:middle line:90%


00:49:23.880 --> 00:49:26.280 align:middle line:90%
Then we declare victory.

00:49:26.280 --> 00:49:33.120 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, we would
have A times A plus A

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:37.880 align:middle line:84%
times A is smaller
than K A times A

00:49:37.880 --> 00:49:43.440 align:middle line:84%
where K is like
p to the epsilon.

00:49:43.440 --> 00:49:45.260 align:middle line:90%
And then we can use Plunnecke.

00:49:45.260 --> 00:49:48.100 align:middle line:90%


00:49:48.100 --> 00:49:50.460 align:middle line:84%
And that would tell
us that A times

00:49:50.460 --> 00:49:58.460 align:middle line:84%
to A big power minus A
times to another big power.

00:49:58.460 --> 00:50:02.820 align:middle line:90%
Here, we could put 4.

00:50:02.820 --> 00:50:08.660 align:middle line:84%
That would be bounded by
K to the eighth A times A.

00:50:08.660 --> 00:50:14.020 align:middle line:84%
And so that would be
bounded by maybe A times p

00:50:14.020 --> 00:50:16.660 align:middle line:84%
to the 10 epsilon or
something like that.

00:50:16.660 --> 00:50:18.700 align:middle line:84%
And this contradicts
the fact that this we

00:50:18.700 --> 00:50:19.920 align:middle line:90%
know this set is big.

00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:27.820 align:middle line:90%


00:50:27.820 --> 00:50:30.460 align:middle line:84%
And case 1 is similar,
but I think maybe I'll

00:50:30.460 --> 00:50:32.020 align:middle line:90%
make that an exercise.

00:50:32.020 --> 00:50:34.730 align:middle line:84%
You can just practice using
Plunnecke and Ruzsa things.

00:50:34.730 --> 00:50:53.110 align:middle line:90%


00:50:53.110 --> 00:50:56.790 align:middle line:90%
And I do one more corollary.

00:50:56.790 --> 00:50:58.990 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you
start with the set A

00:50:58.990 --> 00:51:01.470 align:middle line:84%
and you start multiplying
and adding and subtracting

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:02.870 align:middle line:90%
and see what you get.

00:51:02.870 --> 00:51:07.070 align:middle line:84%
And we've proven that after
you do this operation,

00:51:07.070 --> 00:51:09.590 align:middle line:90%
it gets a bit bigger.

00:51:09.590 --> 00:51:11.510 align:middle line:90%
But suppose you don't just--

00:51:11.510 --> 00:51:13.078 align:middle line:90%
yeah?

00:51:13.078 --> 00:51:13.870 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Question.

00:51:13.870 --> 00:51:17.560 align:middle line:84%
So you said that the idea is
that if you have some arithmetic

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:19.810 align:middle line:84%
progression or geometric
progression, it can be small,

00:51:19.810 --> 00:51:21.790 align:middle line:90%
but it has to be learned.

00:51:21.790 --> 00:51:23.390 align:middle line:84%
Is it possible to
prove that instead

00:51:23.390 --> 00:51:27.310 align:middle line:84%
of the difference of A
times A and A times A,

00:51:27.310 --> 00:51:31.870 align:middle line:84%
you can just say A times A is
large or A plus A is large?

00:51:31.870 --> 00:51:33.490 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: OK, yes,
great question.

00:51:33.490 --> 00:51:36.630 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, so
in the theme of lemma 2

00:51:36.630 --> 00:51:39.670 align:middle line:84%
is we tried to simplify as
much as possible the expression

00:51:39.670 --> 00:51:41.030 align:middle line:90%
that we put here.

00:51:41.030 --> 00:51:45.680 align:middle line:84%
And there is a suggestion how to
make it as simple as possible.

00:51:45.680 --> 00:51:49.120 align:middle line:84%
So then I'm going to erase this
proof and write that as a--

00:51:49.120 --> 00:51:50.320 align:middle line:90%
I'll write it as a theorem.

00:51:50.320 --> 00:51:53.160 align:middle line:90%


00:51:53.160 --> 00:52:04.560 align:middle line:84%
So even better, there is a
theorem Bourgain-Katz-Tao

00:52:04.560 --> 00:52:11.200 align:middle line:84%
So if A is subset
of Fp, A equals p

00:52:11.200 --> 00:52:15.560 align:middle line:84%
to the S 0 less than or
equal to S less than 1,

00:52:15.560 --> 00:52:27.480 align:middle line:84%
then you could take the maximum
of A plus A and A times A,

00:52:27.480 --> 00:52:33.680 align:middle line:84%
and that is bigger than p
to the S plus epsilon of S.

00:52:33.680 --> 00:52:36.820 align:middle line:84%
So this is better than
this, qualitatively.

00:52:36.820 --> 00:52:41.400 align:middle line:90%


00:52:41.400 --> 00:52:44.183 align:middle line:84%
And actually, the word
sum product inequality--

00:52:44.183 --> 00:52:45.600 align:middle line:84%
it could refer to
a lot of things,

00:52:45.600 --> 00:52:49.940 align:middle line:84%
but the inequality it most
often refers to is this one,

00:52:49.940 --> 00:52:53.700 align:middle line:84%
so either the sums
or the products grow.

00:52:53.700 --> 00:52:55.300 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's right.

00:52:55.300 --> 00:52:57.820 align:middle line:84%
So all the stuff
we've seen are steps

00:52:57.820 --> 00:52:59.600 align:middle line:84%
towards the proof
of this theorem,

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:02.220 align:middle line:84%
but there is actually still
some more ideas to get

00:53:02.220 --> 00:53:04.300 align:middle line:90%
all the way down to here.

00:53:04.300 --> 00:53:06.728 align:middle line:84%
And we may or may not end
up doing it in the class.

00:53:06.728 --> 00:53:09.020 align:middle line:84%
It's unclear to me if getting
all the way down to there

00:53:09.020 --> 00:53:13.940 align:middle line:84%
is actually important
in projection theory.

00:53:13.940 --> 00:53:16.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, cool.

00:53:16.800 --> 00:53:20.340 align:middle line:84%
So one goal you might have
in simplifying and clarifying

00:53:20.340 --> 00:53:23.780 align:middle line:84%
this story is to make this
expression as simple as possible

00:53:23.780 --> 00:53:26.020 align:middle line:90%
and get some gain.

00:53:26.020 --> 00:53:28.220 align:middle line:84%
But another goal
that you might have

00:53:28.220 --> 00:53:31.740 align:middle line:84%
is to make this
gain really large,

00:53:31.740 --> 00:53:34.940 align:middle line:84%
and perhaps this expression
will be more complicated.

00:53:34.940 --> 00:53:37.700 align:middle line:90%
And you can also do that.

00:53:37.700 --> 00:53:39.570 align:middle line:90%
So let me make some notation.

00:53:39.570 --> 00:53:42.870 align:middle line:90%


00:53:42.870 --> 00:53:49.030 align:middle line:84%
Let's say poly K of some
polynomials of complexity K,

00:53:49.030 --> 00:53:52.350 align:middle line:84%
so I take A to the
K. So that means

00:53:52.350 --> 00:53:57.630 align:middle line:84%
I multiply K different
elements of A together.

00:53:57.630 --> 00:54:02.630 align:middle line:84%
And then I add K things
like that together.

00:54:02.630 --> 00:54:04.540 align:middle line:84%
And then maybe I also
want some minuses.

00:54:04.540 --> 00:54:09.550 align:middle line:90%


00:54:09.550 --> 00:54:15.580 align:middle line:84%
So A to the K is A
times A times A K times.

00:54:15.580 --> 00:54:19.590 align:middle line:90%


00:54:19.590 --> 00:54:23.910 align:middle line:84%
So these are polynomials
in of complexity.

00:54:23.910 --> 00:54:27.470 align:middle line:84%
And another corollary,
which is at the same level,

00:54:27.470 --> 00:54:30.830 align:middle line:84%
follows easily from
this one is that if we

00:54:30.830 --> 00:54:38.610 align:middle line:84%
have 0 less than S less than
t less than 1 and A is in Fp,

00:54:38.610 --> 00:54:43.010 align:middle line:84%
then there exists some K
that only depends on S and t

00:54:43.010 --> 00:54:50.330 align:middle line:84%
so that for any set A in
any Fp, where the size of A

00:54:50.330 --> 00:54:57.470 align:middle line:84%
is p to the S, the size of poly
K of A is at least p to the t.

00:54:57.470 --> 00:55:08.290 align:middle line:90%


00:55:08.290 --> 00:55:11.050 align:middle line:90%
And the proof of this is easy.

00:55:11.050 --> 00:55:14.000 align:middle line:84%
The proof is use
lemma 2 many times.

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:17.730 align:middle line:90%


00:55:17.730 --> 00:55:21.210 align:middle line:84%
So I start with the set
A. A times A minus A times

00:55:21.210 --> 00:55:22.730 align:middle line:90%
is a bit bigger.

00:55:22.730 --> 00:55:28.490 align:middle line:84%
Call this B. B times B minus B
times B is even a bit bigger.

00:55:28.490 --> 00:55:32.050 align:middle line:84%
And if you think about what B
times B minus B times B means,

00:55:32.050 --> 00:55:36.350 align:middle line:84%
it would fit in poly for an
A, and you keep doing this.

00:55:36.350 --> 00:55:43.740 align:middle line:90%


00:55:43.740 --> 00:55:44.760 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:55:44.760 --> 00:55:48.620 align:middle line:90%


00:55:48.620 --> 00:55:51.320 align:middle line:84%
So these lemmas,
theorems, and stuff,

00:55:51.320 --> 00:55:56.380 align:middle line:84%
they are important
because-- inequality

00:55:56.380 --> 00:56:01.060 align:middle line:84%
and Ruzsa's inequality,
they are important because--

00:56:01.060 --> 00:56:06.860 align:middle line:90%


00:56:06.860 --> 00:56:09.160 align:middle line:84%
so if we see something
like A plus A is small,

00:56:09.160 --> 00:56:12.660 align:middle line:84%
then that tells us that
A has some structure.

00:56:12.660 --> 00:56:14.060 align:middle line:84%
And all these
inequalities, then,

00:56:14.060 --> 00:56:16.620 align:middle line:84%
imply that lots of
other things are small.

00:56:16.620 --> 00:56:19.680 align:middle line:84%
So it's like a
contagious structure.

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:21.420 align:middle line:84%
We input some structure,
but we find out

00:56:21.420 --> 00:56:22.780 align:middle line:90%
more and more structure.

00:56:22.780 --> 00:56:24.700 align:middle line:90%
And that's a very useful tool.

00:56:24.700 --> 00:56:28.780 align:middle line:84%
And so lots of problems that
we see in projection theory,

00:56:28.780 --> 00:56:31.940 align:middle line:84%
it seems to be helpful to try
to phrase them in the form

00:56:31.940 --> 00:56:36.180 align:middle line:84%
that some subset is
small because, then, we

00:56:36.180 --> 00:56:39.530 align:middle line:84%
can use as inequality and we can
find out lots of other things.

00:56:39.530 --> 00:56:43.670 align:middle line:90%


00:56:43.670 --> 00:56:45.210 align:middle line:84%
So in the last
part of the class,

00:56:45.210 --> 00:56:46.852 align:middle line:90%
we will prove this inequality.

00:56:46.852 --> 00:56:49.060 align:middle line:84%
This is the trickiest thing
that we will prove today.

00:56:49.060 --> 00:57:12.390 align:middle line:90%


00:57:12.390 --> 00:57:15.230 align:middle line:84%
So the original proof
of the inequality

00:57:15.230 --> 00:57:18.630 align:middle line:84%
was somewhat
difficult. And there

00:57:18.630 --> 00:57:24.600 align:middle line:84%
was a short proof that was given
by Georgios Petrides about 10

00:57:24.600 --> 00:57:29.790 align:middle line:84%
or 15 years ago, which is
the one that I'll show.

00:57:29.790 --> 00:57:36.260 align:middle line:90%
So it's based on a key lemma.

00:57:36.260 --> 00:57:40.810 align:middle line:90%


00:57:40.810 --> 00:57:49.890 align:middle line:84%
So the lemma says that if A plus
B is at most K times A, then

00:57:49.890 --> 00:57:55.250 align:middle line:84%
there's a subset x contained
in A so that for any set

00:57:55.250 --> 00:58:08.850 align:middle line:84%
C, x plus C plus B divided by
x plus C is also at most K.

00:58:08.850 --> 00:58:10.710 align:middle line:84%
By the way, this top
inequality-- of course,

00:58:10.710 --> 00:58:15.850 align:middle line:84%
we can divide by A. The top
inequality says A plus B over A

00:58:15.850 --> 00:58:23.970 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by K. The lemma
says that if this is true,

00:58:23.970 --> 00:58:26.690 align:middle line:84%
if it's true for
the set A, then it's

00:58:26.690 --> 00:58:32.470 align:middle line:84%
also true for the set x plus
C, where x is carefully chosen.

00:58:32.470 --> 00:58:34.510 align:middle line:84%
I'll explain in a
bit how it's chosen,

00:58:34.510 --> 00:58:36.392 align:middle line:84%
but C is a totally
arbitrary set.

00:58:36.392 --> 00:58:38.100 align:middle line:84%
So there are many
choices for C. So there

00:58:38.100 --> 00:58:41.280 align:middle line:84%
are many different-- this
is many inequalities.

00:58:41.280 --> 00:58:47.320 align:middle line:90%


00:58:47.320 --> 00:58:49.940 align:middle line:84%
Let me tell you
who x is, which is

00:58:49.940 --> 00:58:51.370 align:middle line:90%
an important idea in the proof.

00:58:51.370 --> 00:58:54.420 align:middle line:90%


00:58:54.420 --> 00:58:58.420 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, so
x is a subset of A

00:58:58.420 --> 00:59:07.660 align:middle line:84%
that we choose in order
to minimize the ratio x

00:59:07.660 --> 00:59:09.250 align:middle line:90%
plus B over x.

00:59:09.250 --> 00:59:13.940 align:middle line:90%


00:59:13.940 --> 00:59:17.060 align:middle line:84%
So let me give an
example that might

00:59:17.060 --> 00:59:22.540 align:middle line:84%
help to motivate why you
would want to look at this x.

00:59:22.540 --> 00:59:27.820 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that A is the
numbers from 1 up to 100,

00:59:27.820 --> 00:59:31.260 align:middle line:84%
which has a lot of
additive structure

00:59:31.260 --> 00:59:33.460 align:middle line:84%
together with some
random number.

00:59:33.460 --> 00:59:34.690 align:middle line:90%
So I put a million.

00:59:34.690 --> 00:59:38.430 align:middle line:90%


00:59:38.430 --> 00:59:42.240 align:middle line:84%
And B is the numbers
from 1 up to, say, 50.

00:59:42.240 --> 00:59:44.790 align:middle line:90%


00:59:44.790 --> 00:59:49.750 align:middle line:84%
So if you add A and B together,
this stuff plus this stuff

00:59:49.750 --> 00:59:51.350 align:middle line:90%
is quite small.

00:59:51.350 --> 00:59:53.203 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of
structure there.

00:59:53.203 --> 00:59:54.870 align:middle line:84%
Then there's this
stuff plus this stuff.

00:59:54.870 --> 00:59:57.253 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't have any
particular structure.

00:59:57.253 --> 00:59:59.170 align:middle line:84%
But since there's only
one stray element here,

00:59:59.170 --> 01:00:01.310 align:middle line:84%
that's not so many
of those either.

01:00:01.310 --> 01:00:04.270 align:middle line:90%
So A plus B is pretty small.

01:00:04.270 --> 01:00:05.590 align:middle line:90%
Now, who would x be?

01:00:05.590 --> 01:00:08.230 align:middle line:90%


01:00:08.230 --> 01:00:12.920 align:middle line:84%
x was the subset of A which is
chosen to minimize this ratio.

01:00:12.920 --> 01:00:15.510 align:middle line:90%


01:00:15.510 --> 01:00:18.720 align:middle line:84%
And including this
guy is not so helpful.

01:00:18.720 --> 01:00:21.950 align:middle line:90%


01:00:21.950 --> 01:00:24.070 align:middle line:84%
So x would actually
be here, just

01:00:24.070 --> 01:00:31.510 align:middle line:90%
the numbers from 1 up to 100.

01:00:31.510 --> 01:00:34.390 align:middle line:84%
So I think perhaps
that, philosophically,

01:00:34.390 --> 01:00:38.290 align:middle line:84%
the point of doing this is
identifying the part of A that

01:00:38.290 --> 01:00:40.290 align:middle line:84%
really has the
additive structure

01:00:40.290 --> 01:00:42.650 align:middle line:84%
and throwing away, possibly,
some parts of A that

01:00:42.650 --> 01:00:46.050 align:middle line:90%
are not that relevant.

01:00:46.050 --> 01:00:50.210 align:middle line:84%
And then, once you have found
the heart of the matter here,

01:00:50.210 --> 01:00:55.990 align:middle line:84%
then you can add
anything else to it.

01:00:55.990 --> 01:00:58.270 align:middle line:84%
And you still have that
amount of structure.

01:00:58.270 --> 01:01:22.030 align:middle line:90%


01:01:22.030 --> 01:01:23.310 align:middle line:90%
So let's give a name.

01:01:23.310 --> 01:01:26.150 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that--
so that's who x is.

01:01:26.150 --> 01:01:31.300 align:middle line:84%
And let's say x plus B over x is
K lower bar, which is at most K.

01:01:31.300 --> 01:01:38.620 align:middle line:84%
So A plus B over A is at most K.
And x is allowed to be all of A.

01:01:38.620 --> 01:01:40.420 align:middle line:84%
But we might choose a
smaller set if we can

01:01:40.420 --> 01:01:42.900 align:middle line:90%
make this ratio even smaller.

01:01:42.900 --> 01:01:46.460 align:middle line:84%
So K bar is less
than or equal to K.

01:01:46.460 --> 01:01:53.740 align:middle line:84%
And really, the key claim is
that x plus C plus B over x

01:01:53.740 --> 01:01:59.430 align:middle line:84%
plus C is at most K
lower bar for any x.

01:01:59.430 --> 01:02:06.540 align:middle line:90%


01:02:06.540 --> 01:02:11.040 align:middle line:84%
So now we're going to prove
the claim by induction.

01:02:11.040 --> 01:02:13.780 align:middle line:90%


01:02:13.780 --> 01:02:19.980 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to prove
the claim by induction

01:02:19.980 --> 01:02:26.980 align:middle line:84%
on the cardinality of C. And
the cardinality of C is 1.

01:02:26.980 --> 01:02:36.710 align:middle line:84%
Then x plus C plus B is just x
plus B. And x plus C is just x.

01:02:36.710 --> 01:02:40.290 align:middle line:84%
So if the cardinality of C is
1, I'm just shifting this set.

01:02:40.290 --> 01:02:44.230 align:middle line:84%
And shifting that set doesn't
change their cardinality.

01:02:44.230 --> 01:02:46.400 align:middle line:84%
So now we can do
the inductive step.

01:02:46.400 --> 01:02:59.610 align:middle line:90%


01:02:59.610 --> 01:03:03.490 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that C
prime is C union--

01:03:03.490 --> 01:03:05.070 align:middle line:90%
one more guy.

01:03:05.070 --> 01:03:08.510 align:middle line:84%
And by induction, we know
that it's true for C.

01:03:08.510 --> 01:03:16.390 align:middle line:84%
So we know x plus C plus B is
bounded by K lower bar x plus C.

01:03:16.390 --> 01:03:17.880 align:middle line:84%
And we want to
check for C prime.

01:03:17.880 --> 01:03:32.810 align:middle line:90%


01:03:32.810 --> 01:03:37.490 align:middle line:84%
So the key character in this
argument that Petrides came up

01:03:37.490 --> 01:03:43.490 align:middle line:84%
with is a set y, which
is the set of x and X

01:03:43.490 --> 01:03:48.410 align:middle line:84%
so that x plus little
C plus B is contained

01:03:48.410 --> 01:03:53.890 align:middle line:84%
in big X plus big C plus B.
Let's see how that naturally

01:03:53.890 --> 01:03:54.750 align:middle line:90%
comes up.

01:03:54.750 --> 01:04:06.490 align:middle line:90%


01:04:06.490 --> 01:04:13.250 align:middle line:84%
So we're thinking about x
plus C prime plus B. We want

01:04:13.250 --> 01:04:14.930 align:middle line:90%
to see that it's not too big.

01:04:14.930 --> 01:04:16.110 align:middle line:90%
And we're using induction.

01:04:16.110 --> 01:04:19.970 align:middle line:84%
So we want to see how it changes
when we added this one guy.

01:04:19.970 --> 01:04:30.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is the previous guy, x
plus C plus B plus the new ones,

01:04:30.380 --> 01:04:32.280 align:middle line:84%
and I want them
to be really new.

01:04:32.280 --> 01:04:37.700 align:middle line:90%


01:04:37.700 --> 01:04:40.740 align:middle line:84%
So here are some new
elements that live here,

01:04:40.740 --> 01:04:43.550 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to take out any
elements I've already counted.

01:04:43.550 --> 01:04:49.812 align:middle line:90%


01:04:49.812 --> 01:04:56.100 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Sorry, I don't quite
understand the definition

01:04:56.100 --> 01:05:05.940 align:middle line:84%
of how can x plus C plus B not
be a subset of x plus C plus B.

01:05:05.940 --> 01:05:09.100 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So C prime
is a previous set C

01:05:09.100 --> 01:05:11.740 align:middle line:90%
union with some little c.

01:05:11.740 --> 01:05:14.940 align:middle line:84%
And little c is
not in big C. Now

01:05:14.940 --> 01:05:18.340 align:middle line:84%
I have to write all the little
c's and big Cs really carefully.

01:05:18.340 --> 01:05:24.520 align:middle line:84%
But this is a little c,
and this is a big C. Cool.

01:05:24.520 --> 01:05:27.440 align:middle line:84%
So this x is
automatically in big X,

01:05:27.440 --> 01:05:30.620 align:middle line:84%
but in a failure of
functoriality of notation,

01:05:30.620 --> 01:05:45.280 align:middle line:90%
little c is not in big C.

01:05:45.280 --> 01:05:48.400 align:middle line:84%
Now, one thing to note
about this definition that

01:05:48.400 --> 01:05:52.640 align:middle line:84%
helps to motivate it is that
y plus little C plus big B

01:05:52.640 --> 01:05:58.920 align:middle line:84%
is contained in x
plus big C plus big B

01:05:58.920 --> 01:06:03.160 align:middle line:84%
because for each element
of y, little y plus little

01:06:03.160 --> 01:06:05.820 align:middle line:84%
c plus big B is
defined to be in here.

01:06:05.820 --> 01:06:08.520 align:middle line:90%


01:06:08.520 --> 01:06:17.720 align:middle line:84%
So this is at most x plus c
plus B plus x plus c plus B

01:06:17.720 --> 01:06:26.050 align:middle line:90%
take away y plus c plus B.

01:06:26.050 --> 01:06:28.270 align:middle line:84%
All of these were
already counted.

01:06:28.270 --> 01:06:30.420 align:middle line:84%
So there are at most
this many new guys.

01:06:30.420 --> 01:06:33.810 align:middle line:90%


01:06:33.810 --> 01:06:42.130 align:middle line:84%
And this is x plus C plus B
plus x plus B minus y plus B

01:06:42.130 --> 01:06:44.890 align:middle line:84%
because this is
a subset of this.

01:06:44.890 --> 01:06:49.010 align:middle line:84%
And the plus c just
translates things.

01:06:49.010 --> 01:06:52.390 align:middle line:84%
So this thing is that big and
I remove from it this thing,

01:06:52.390 --> 01:06:55.530 align:middle line:90%
which is that big.

01:06:55.530 --> 01:06:59.550 align:middle line:84%
So that's the upper
bound for the numerator.

01:06:59.550 --> 01:07:05.506 align:middle line:90%


01:07:05.506 --> 01:07:10.170 align:middle line:84%
So I'm trying to bound
this thing with a C prime.

01:07:10.170 --> 01:07:12.290 align:middle line:84%
I want to prove an upper
bound, so an upper bound

01:07:12.290 --> 01:07:15.070 align:middle line:84%
for the numerator and a lower
bound for the denominator.

01:07:15.070 --> 01:07:39.220 align:middle line:90%


01:07:39.220 --> 01:07:45.940 align:middle line:84%
So the denominator
is x plus C prime.

01:07:45.940 --> 01:07:54.780 align:middle line:84%
And so that's x plus C plus
the set how many x and x.

01:07:54.780 --> 01:07:57.860 align:middle line:84%
So that little x
plus little c is not

01:07:57.860 --> 01:08:04.580 align:middle line:84%
contained in big X
plus big C. So the guys

01:08:04.580 --> 01:08:07.260 align:middle line:84%
I already had, and then
I have guys of the form

01:08:07.260 --> 01:08:09.460 align:middle line:90%
little x plus little c.

01:08:09.460 --> 01:08:10.840 align:middle line:90%
And I only want the new ones.

01:08:10.840 --> 01:08:13.460 align:middle line:84%
The ones that aren't
already counted.

01:08:13.460 --> 01:08:15.340 align:middle line:90%
So that's an equality.

01:08:15.340 --> 01:08:23.760 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to write it as x
plus c plus x minus the x and x

01:08:23.760 --> 01:08:27.899 align:middle line:90%
so that x plus c is in x plus c.

01:08:27.899 --> 01:08:34.359 align:middle line:90%


01:08:34.359 --> 01:08:39.500 align:middle line:84%
And now the key observation is
that these guys are all in y.

01:08:39.500 --> 01:08:42.880 align:middle line:90%


01:08:42.880 --> 01:08:48.080 align:middle line:84%
This is a subset of y because
if little x plus little c

01:08:48.080 --> 01:08:51.560 align:middle line:90%
is In big X plus big C--

01:08:51.560 --> 01:08:56.000 align:middle line:84%
so if little x plus little
c is in big X plus big C,

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:57.540 align:middle line:90%
then I can add B to both sides.

01:08:57.540 --> 01:09:00.000 align:middle line:90%
And this is in there.

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:01.220 align:middle line:90%
So those are all in y.

01:09:01.220 --> 01:09:04.840 align:middle line:90%


01:09:04.840 --> 01:09:07.600 align:middle line:90%
So this is a subset of y.

01:09:07.600 --> 01:09:10.840 align:middle line:84%
So the size of this guy
is at most the size of y.

01:09:10.840 --> 01:09:12.319 align:middle line:84%
And since I'm
subtracting here, I

01:09:12.319 --> 01:09:17.380 align:middle line:84%
can say this is at least
x plus c plus x minus y.

01:09:17.380 --> 01:09:27.689 align:middle line:90%


01:09:27.689 --> 01:09:30.750 align:middle line:84%
So now we'll just put together
everything that we know.

01:09:30.750 --> 01:09:36.529 align:middle line:90%


01:09:36.529 --> 01:09:45.970 align:middle line:84%
We know that x plus C plus B
over x plus C is at most K bar.

01:09:45.970 --> 01:09:47.470 align:middle line:90%
We know that by induction.

01:09:47.470 --> 01:09:51.370 align:middle line:90%


01:09:51.370 --> 01:09:57.250 align:middle line:84%
We know that x plus B
over x is equal to K bar.

01:09:57.250 --> 01:09:59.130 align:middle line:90%
We know that by definition.

01:09:59.130 --> 01:10:00.510 align:middle line:90%
That's just what K bar was.

01:10:00.510 --> 01:10:03.170 align:middle line:90%


01:10:03.170 --> 01:10:08.170 align:middle line:84%
And we know that
y plus B over y is

01:10:08.170 --> 01:10:10.650 align:middle line:90%
greater than or equal to K bar.

01:10:10.650 --> 01:10:13.290 align:middle line:90%
That was the definition of x.

01:10:13.290 --> 01:10:16.690 align:middle line:84%
x was chosen to
minimize this ratio.

01:10:16.690 --> 01:10:18.580 align:middle line:90%
y might perhaps be equal to x.

01:10:18.580 --> 01:10:20.040 align:middle line:90%
But that's OK.

01:10:20.040 --> 01:10:21.690 align:middle line:84%
But it's never going
to be any smaller.

01:10:21.690 --> 01:10:26.740 align:middle line:90%


01:10:26.740 --> 01:10:31.700 align:middle line:84%
And so therefore, by algebra,
by how fractions work,

01:10:31.700 --> 01:10:33.680 align:middle line:90%
x plus C plus B--

01:10:33.680 --> 01:10:34.440 align:middle line:90%
oh, sorry.

01:10:34.440 --> 01:10:37.180 align:middle line:90%
So now I can say--

01:10:37.180 --> 01:10:43.120 align:middle line:84%
I want to say x plus C prime
plus B over x plus C prime,

01:10:43.120 --> 01:10:46.200 align:middle line:84%
and I want an upper
bound for that.

01:10:46.200 --> 01:10:49.780 align:middle line:84%
So the numerator
is bounded by 1 x

01:10:49.780 --> 01:10:56.700 align:middle line:84%
plus C plus B plus x
plus B minus y plus B.

01:10:56.700 --> 01:11:00.540 align:middle line:84%
And the denominator is
lower bounded by part two.

01:11:00.540 --> 01:11:05.080 align:middle line:84%
And it's x plus
C plus x minus y.

01:11:05.080 --> 01:11:07.740 align:middle line:90%


01:11:07.740 --> 01:11:12.300 align:middle line:84%
And then because each of these
ratios has the correct sign,

01:11:12.300 --> 01:11:14.440 align:middle line:90%
this is at most K lower bar.

01:11:14.440 --> 01:11:21.400 align:middle line:90%


01:11:21.400 --> 01:11:22.460 align:middle line:90%
So this is short.

01:11:22.460 --> 01:11:23.443 align:middle line:90%
It is a little tricky.

01:11:23.443 --> 01:11:25.360 align:middle line:84%
And I must admit, I don't
quite understand how

01:11:25.360 --> 01:11:26.820 align:middle line:90%
Petrides thought to do this.

01:11:26.820 --> 01:11:59.240 align:middle line:90%


01:11:59.240 --> 01:12:04.000 align:middle line:84%
So from the key lemma, we can
prove Plunnecke inequality

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:08.840 align:middle line:90%
and then see if anybody--

01:12:08.840 --> 01:12:13.280 align:middle line:84%
if you have room, you can
turn over in your mind,

01:12:13.280 --> 01:12:16.490 align:middle line:84%
philosophically, why did
this work out so nicely?

01:12:16.490 --> 01:12:18.990 align:middle line:84%
If anybody has thoughts about
it, I would be happy to hear.

01:12:18.990 --> 01:12:41.330 align:middle line:90%


01:12:41.330 --> 01:12:45.920 align:middle line:84%
So proof-- so say we're
starting with this.

01:12:45.920 --> 01:12:52.490 align:middle line:90%


01:12:52.490 --> 01:12:57.610 align:middle line:84%
So we use our main
lemma, so it tells us

01:12:57.610 --> 01:13:00.410 align:middle line:84%
that there exists
some x in A, and we

01:13:00.410 --> 01:13:09.770 align:middle line:84%
have x plus C plus B is at most
K times x plus C for any C.

01:13:09.770 --> 01:13:10.880 align:middle line:90%
How might we use this?

01:13:10.880 --> 01:13:16.410 align:middle line:90%


01:13:16.410 --> 01:13:18.070 align:middle line:90%
So C could be empty.

01:13:18.070 --> 01:13:23.422 align:middle line:84%
So we get x plus B
is at most K times x.

01:13:23.422 --> 01:13:31.070 align:middle line:84%
C could be B, so we get x plus
B plus B. That's at most K times

01:13:31.070 --> 01:13:36.130 align:middle line:84%
x plus B. And x plus B
is at most K times x.

01:13:36.130 --> 01:13:38.770 align:middle line:84%
So that's at most
K squared times x.

01:13:38.770 --> 01:13:41.710 align:middle line:90%


01:13:41.710 --> 01:13:44.330 align:middle line:90%
And you can see where this goes.

01:13:44.330 --> 01:13:45.410 align:middle line:90%
So I'll do one more.

01:13:45.410 --> 01:13:46.950 align:middle line:90%
You'll get the pattern.

01:13:46.950 --> 01:13:49.510 align:middle line:84%
If I add one more
B, That's at most

01:13:49.510 --> 01:13:54.450 align:middle line:84%
K X plus B plus B. Plug in what
I already know about this--

01:13:54.450 --> 01:13:57.730 align:middle line:90%
that's at most k cubed times x.

01:13:57.730 --> 01:14:01.670 align:middle line:84%
So if I add x plus
m copies of B,

01:14:01.670 --> 01:14:04.210 align:middle line:84%
that will be at most
k to the m times x.

01:14:04.210 --> 01:14:10.234 align:middle line:90%


01:14:10.234 --> 01:14:16.300 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll use
the Ruzsa inequality.

01:14:16.300 --> 01:14:23.680 align:middle line:84%
So this is already
pretty good thing.

01:14:23.680 --> 01:14:28.360 align:middle line:84%
If A equals B here, then
I could say A to the m

01:14:28.360 --> 01:14:32.520 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by K to the m
times A because A to the m

01:14:32.520 --> 01:14:36.240 align:middle line:84%
is obviously at least as
big as x plus A to the m.

01:14:36.240 --> 01:14:38.720 align:middle line:84%
So I get A to the m is
bounded by K to the m times

01:14:38.720 --> 01:14:41.840 align:middle line:84%
A. That's a typical
corollary of Plunnecke.

01:14:41.840 --> 01:14:44.780 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, to get the
advertised finale,

01:14:44.780 --> 01:14:47.280 align:middle line:90%
we use Ruzsa's inequality.

01:14:47.280 --> 01:14:49.260 align:middle line:90%
Ruzsa was A times--

01:14:49.260 --> 01:14:57.240 align:middle line:90%


01:14:57.240 --> 01:15:01.340 align:middle line:90%
so I can plug in--

01:15:01.340 --> 01:15:08.000 align:middle line:90%


01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:14.850 align:middle line:84%
so x times B plus
m minus B plus n

01:15:14.850 --> 01:15:22.390 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by x plus B
plus m x plus B plus n.

01:15:22.390 --> 01:15:27.090 align:middle line:90%


01:15:27.090 --> 01:15:29.850 align:middle line:84%
And then we plug
in each of these,

01:15:29.850 --> 01:15:37.800 align:middle line:84%
and we get a K to the m
plus n times x squared.

01:15:37.800 --> 01:15:41.570 align:middle line:90%


01:15:41.570 --> 01:15:42.690 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's right.

01:15:42.690 --> 01:15:46.130 align:middle line:90%
So then I get this by itself.

01:15:46.130 --> 01:15:51.410 align:middle line:84%
So B plus m minus B
plus n is bounded by K

01:15:51.410 --> 01:15:54.370 align:middle line:84%
to the m plus n
times x, which is

01:15:54.370 --> 01:15:57.290 align:middle line:84%
bounded by K to the
m plus n times A

01:15:57.290 --> 01:16:23.730 align:middle line:90%
because x is a subset of A.

01:16:23.730 --> 01:16:25.450 align:middle line:90%
So this proof is short.

01:16:25.450 --> 01:16:26.950 align:middle line:90%
It is a little tricky.

01:16:26.950 --> 01:16:28.870 align:middle line:84%
But I think it is
well worth spending

01:16:28.870 --> 01:16:32.670 align:middle line:84%
some time with because
this inequality is really

01:16:32.670 --> 01:16:33.850 align:middle line:90%
quite important.

01:16:33.850 --> 01:16:36.710 align:middle line:84%
I would say that it
plays really a key role

01:16:36.710 --> 01:16:39.750 align:middle line:84%
in all the later developments
in projection theory

01:16:39.750 --> 01:16:44.510 align:middle line:84%
and the solution to the
problem in a lot of things.

01:16:44.510 --> 01:16:48.810 align:middle line:84%
And so as we keep going
tomorrow or Thursday and so on,

01:16:48.810 --> 01:16:53.350 align:middle line:84%
we'll reflect more about why
this is useful and important.

01:16:53.350 --> 01:16:56.470 align:middle line:84%
And maybe I'll try to
come up with some homework

01:16:56.470 --> 01:17:00.400 align:middle line:84%
to try to reflect on how
this proof got put together.

01:17:00.400 --> 01:17:03.110 align:middle line:90%


01:17:03.110 --> 01:17:04.660 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:17:04.660 --> 01:17:09.000 align:middle line:90%